<TITLE> UK retail sales fall in Oct, 1st time since Jan </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Nov 15 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British retail sales fell in October for the first time in nine months, suggesting consumer spending is slowing from its recent heady pace and reinforcing expectations for lower interest rates ahead. Sterling tumbled after Thursday's weaker than expected report, which also showed sales growth in September was only half as strong as initially reported. The Office for National Statistics said sales fell 0.1 percent last month, putting them up 4.4 percent on the year. Sales growth in September was halved to 0.3 percent. "Retail sales have been surprisingly elevated for some time now and today's data shows that this is starting to unwind," said Alan Clarke at BNP Paribas. "Overall, a bad outcome that adds weight to our call that the Bank of England will not wait until February before cutting interest rates -- December is our bet." The central bank on Wednesday cut its growth forecasts and signalled two interest rate cuts could be on the cards for next year. The biggest fall came from clothing and footwear stores where milder weather depressed sales, the ONS said. Food stores also registered a decline following steep price increases in this sector. Overall, however, prices were on average 1.1 percent lower than a year ago compared with a decline of 1.5 percent in Septemb
